). In uninduced conditions, the expression of these proteins within bacteria was low or undetectable (bac, no NTA,
), suggesting the dominant expression and secretion of parental PcrV. Analysis of the molecules in this phenotypic group may help to understand possible differential features of PcrV distinct to translocation or secretion. To further analyze the deregulated secretion/translocation-competent phenotype, class III derivatives were compared for the localization on the bacterial surface by flow cytometry. In the absence of NTA (uninduced), all of the derivatives localized on the bacterial surface similar to PcrV (open bars,
